Trapezila. Goeller, Lindemann, and Ritschl would allow the second syllable in Trapeaila to be short, on the authority of Trin. 11. iv. 23 (Senam), ¹

But although the first syllable in drachma must be long, it by no means follows that the first syllable in drachuma is also long; on the contrary, we should be justified in asserting that it maest be short, for the Greelr δραχμὴ is naturally short, and accordingly being followedby the aspiratcd mute χ and the liquid μ appears as short in Aristop. Hence all difficulty as to the scansion of the above line vanishes, and it is unnecessary to have recourse to the expedient of pronouncing malle as amonosyllable. Philippus, philippens, Philippicas. The case of these words is peculiar, and demands special notice. They occur upwards of thirty times in Plautus with reference to gold coin, and in every instance, except perhaps one, to be noticed below, the two first syllables are to be pronounced as one—Phlippus, Phlippeus. (Phi- lippeus however does not occur in nominative sing.) This cannot be occidental, but must have resultcd from the ordinary pronun· clation of the word, for the form Philippus would be quite as ser- viceable in an Iambic or Trochaic line as Phlr'ppus. Again, Phr’lppeus, Philippeo, Philippei, lec, seem sometimes pronounced as trisyllables, Phhppiirs, ac, but more frequently as dissyllables, PhlippeTs, lec, never as tetrasyllables, Philippiis. Phrlppicum occurs once only, and must be pronounced Phlippicum. Thus Poen. 1. iii. 6 (senaa),
